# CLAUDE.md — Research-Heavy Project

A CLAUDE.md for projects where correctness, rigor, and traceability matter most. Suited for data analysis, scientific computing, research tools, or any codebase where wrong results are worse than slow results.

Copy this file to your project root as `CLAUDE.md`.

---

## How You Should Operate

### Correctness Over Speed
Getting it right matters more than getting it done fast. If you're not confident an approach is correct, say so and explain your reasoning. Take time to think through edge cases, numerical stability, off-by-one errors, and boundary conditions. An honest "I'm not sure this handles X correctly" prevents bad data from entering the pipeline.

### Show Your Reasoning
This project requires traceable decisions. When you write code, explain the logic — especially mathematical operations, data transformations, and algorithmic choices. Comments should explain WHY, not WHAT. If you're implementing a formula or algorithm, cite the source or describe the derivation.

### Verify Assumptions
Don't assume inputs are clean, distributions are normal, or edge cases are rare. State your assumptions explicitly. If a function assumes sorted input, say so. If a statistical method requires certain conditions, check them or document them as prerequisites.

### Flag Uncertainty
If you're not familiar with a domain-specific method or library, say so. If you're implementing something based on your understanding rather than a verified reference, flag it for review. In research code, "I think this is right" is useful information. Silently guessing isn't.

## Technical Standards

- Write code that can be audited. Favor clarity over cleverness. A straightforward implementation that someone can verify line-by-line beats an optimized one that requires deep expertise to validate.
- Include unit tests for any non-trivial computation. Test edge cases and known values.
- When working with data: validate inputs, check outputs against expectations, log anomalies.
- Document units, coordinate systems, index conventions, and any other domain context that code alone doesn't convey.

## Data Handling

- Never silently drop or modify data. If a cleaning step removes records, log what was removed and why.
- Preserve raw data. Transformations should produce new outputs, not modify inputs in place.
- If a result looks surprising, flag it. Unusual results are either discoveries or bugs — both deserve attention.

## When You're Stuck

- Describe what you're trying to do, what approach you've taken, and where specifically you're uncertain. This is more useful than repeatedly trying variations.
- If a problem requires domain expertise you don't have, say so. Point me to the specific decision that needs expert input.
- If two approaches seem equivalent and you can't determine which is more appropriate, present both with trade-offs rather than picking one arbitrarily.

## What I Don't Want

- Black-box implementations. If I can't trace the logic from input to output, it doesn't belong in research code.
- Silent assumptions about data quality or distribution.
- Optimizations that sacrifice readability without measured justification.
- "It works on the test data" without analysis of why it works and when it might not.
